# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1898-boston-beaneaters-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1898-boston-beaneaters-season/1871-boston-red-stockings-season] The 1871 season was the first season of the Boston Red Stockings franchise, now known as the Atlanta Braves.
[src:1898-boston-beaneaters-season/1871-boston-red-stockings-season] They were formed in 1871 by Boston businessman and Ashburnham native Ivers Whitney Adams.
[src:1898-boston-beaneaters-season/1871-boston-red-stockings-season] The team was composed of former players of the defunct Cincinnati Red Stockings franchise, who were brought to Boston and kept the name with them.
[src:1898-boston-beaneaters-season/1871-boston-red-stockings-season] Led and managed by baseball pioneer Harry Wright, the new Boston team would join the newly formed National Association of Professional Base Ball Players for the 1871 season and finish the year in third place with a record of 20–10.
[src:1898-boston-beaneaters-season/1871-boston-red-stockings-season] Pitcher Al Spalding started all 31 of the Red Stockings' games and led the NA with 19 wins.
[src:1898-boston-beaneaters-season/1871-boston-red-stockings-season] Catcher Cal McVey finished second in the league batting race with a .431 average.
[src:1898-boston-beaneaters-season/1871-boston-red-stockings-season] From this team, Harry Wright, Al Spalding, and shortstop George Wright have all been elected into the Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:1898-boston-beaneaters-season/1871-major-league-baseball-season] The tenth founding member, the National club of Washington, did not enter a team for the championship until 1872.
[src:1898-boston-beaneaters-season/1872-boston-red-stockings-season] The **1872 Boston Red Stockings season** was the second season of the franchise.
[src:1898-boston-beaneaters-season/1872-boston-red-stockings-season] They won the National Association championship.
[src:1898-boston-beaneaters-season/1872-boston-red-stockings-season] Managed by Harry Wright, Boston finished with a record of 39–8 to win the pennant by 7.5 games.
[src:1898-boston-beaneaters-season/1872-boston-red-stockings-season] Pitcher Al Spalding started all 48 of the Red Stockings' games and led the NA with 38 wins.
[src:1898-boston-beaneaters-season/1872-boston-red-stockings-season] Second baseman Ross Barnes won the league batting title with a .430 batting average.
[src:1898-boston-beaneaters-season/1872-boston-red-stockings-season] Harry Wright, Al Spalding, and shortstop George Wright have all been elected into the Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:1898-boston-beaneaters-season/1872-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1872 throughout the world.
[src:1898-boston-beaneaters-season/1873-boston-red-stockings-season] The **1873 Boston Red Stockings season** was the third season of the franchise.
[src:1898-boston-beaneaters-season/1873-boston-red-stockings-season] They won their second consecutive National Association championship.
[src:1898-boston-beaneaters-season/1873-boston-red-stockings-season] Managed by Harry Wright, Boston finished with a record of 43–16 to win the pennant by 4 games.
[src:1898-boston-beaneaters-season/1873-boston-red-stockings-season] Pitcher Al Spalding started 54 of the Red Stockings' games and led the NA with 41 wins.
[src:1898-boston-beaneaters-season/1873-boston-red-stockings-season] Second baseman Ross Barnes won the league batting title with a .431 batting average, and catcher Deacon White topped the circuit with 77 runs batted in.
[src:1898-boston-beaneaters-season/1873-boston-red-stockings-season] Harry Wright, Al Spalding, first baseman Jim O'Rourke, and shortstop George Wright have all been elected into the Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:1898-boston-beaneaters-season/1874-boston-red-stockings-season] The **1874 Boston Red Stockings season** was the fourth season of the franchise.
[src:1898-boston-beaneaters-season/1874-boston-red-stockings-season] They won their third consecutive National Association championship.
[src:1898-boston-beaneaters-season/1874-boston-red-stockings-season] Managed by Harry Wright, Boston finished with a record of 52–18 to win the pennant by 7.5 games.
[src:1898-boston-beaneaters-season/1874-boston-red-stockings-season] Pitcher Al Spalding started 69 of the Red Stockings' games and led the NA with 52 wins.
[src:1898-boston-beaneaters-season/1874-boston-red-stockings-season] Outfielder Cal McVey led the league with 71 runs batted in, and he paced the Boston offense which scored more runs than any other team.
[src:1898-boston-beaneaters-season/1874-boston-red-stockings-season] Harry Wright, Al Spalding, first baseman Jim O'Rourke, catcher Deacon White, and shortstop George Wright have all been elected into the Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:1898-boston-beaneaters-season/1875-boston-red-stockings-season] The **1875 Boston Red Stockings season** was the fifth season of the Boston Red Stockings franchise.
[src:1898-boston-beaneaters-season/1875-boston-red-stockings-season] They won their fourth consecutive National Association championship.
[src:1898-boston-beaneaters-season/1875-boston-red-stockings-season] Managed by Harry Wright, Boston finished with a record of 71–8 to win the pennant by 15 games.
[src:1898-boston-beaneaters-season/1875-boston-red-stockings-season] Pitcher Al Spalding started 62 of the Red Stockings' games and led the NA with 54 wins.
[src:1898-boston-beaneaters-season/1875-boston-red-stockings-season] Catcher Deacon White (.367), second baseman Ross Barnes (.364), and first baseman Cal McVey (.355) finished 1–2–3 in the league's batting race.
[src:1898-boston-beaneaters-season/1875-boston-red-stockings-season] McVey paced the circuit with 87 runs batted in, and outfielder Jim O'Rourke had the most home runs, with 6.
[src:1898-boston-beaneaters-season/1875-boston-red-stockings-season] The Boston offense scored more runs than any other team in the NA.
[src:1898-boston-beaneaters-season/1875-boston-red-stockings-season] Harry Wright, Al Spalding, Jim O'Rourke, and shortstop George Wright have all been elected into the Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:1898-boston-beaneaters-season/1875-boston-red-stockings-season] This was the last season of the Association, which dissolved at the end of the year.
[src:1898-boston-beaneaters-season/1875-boston-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings club would join the new National League in 1876.
[src:1898-boston-beaneaters-season/1898-boston-beaneaters-season] The **1898 Boston Beaneaters season** was the 28th season of the franchise.
[src:1898-boston-beaneaters-season/1898-boston-beaneaters-season] The Beaneaters had a record of 102–47–3 (.685), finishing 6.0 games ahead of the second-place Baltimore Orioles and winning their second straight National League pennant and their eighth overall.
[src:1898-boston-beaneaters-season/1898-boston-beaneaters-season] It was also their fifth, and last, of the decade.
[src:1898-boston-beaneaters-season/1898-boston-beaneaters-season] This team has been cited (along with the 1880s St.
[src:1898-boston-beaneaters-season/1898-boston-beaneaters-season] Louis Browns and the 1890s Baltimore Orioles) as one of the greatest of the 19th century.
[src:1898-boston-beaneaters-season/1898-boston-beaneaters-season] This was the end of a tremendous run of success for the team, which won four straight National Association titles (1872–1875) and eight National League pennants (1877, 1878, 1883, 1891–1893, 1897-1898).
[src:1898-boston-beaneaters-season/1898-boston-beaneaters-season] The starting line-up featured three Hall of Famers: third baseman Jimmy Collins and outfielders Billy Hamilton and Hugh Duffy.
[src:1898-boston-beaneaters-season/1898-boston-beaneaters-season] Collins led the league with 15 home runs and Hamilton had a batting average of .369 with 54 stolen bases.
[src:1898-boston-beaneaters-season/1898-boston-beaneaters-season] The pitching staff was led by Hall of Famers Kid Nichols and Vic Willis.
[src:1898-boston-beaneaters-season/1898-boston-beaneaters-season] Nichols led the NL with 31 wins and had an earned run average (ERA) of 2.13.
